""This is the story Queen who no longer feared death..of a King who helped her laugh again...."" (I'm paraphrasing here  please bear with me.) " #BelieverBC  Overall the chapter was  well written. However I did have some issues with it  and I'll explain the the best that I can. First  as a prologue  it feels more like a chapter one. A prologue should be shorter  so I would reconsider the titling of this piece. Second  you use a lot of suddenly  and thens in the narrative. The problem with using words like And then  or suddenly  is that it takes away from the immediacy of the scene. We are taken away from the story by thinking of the word suddenly  so it becomes something that kind of weakens the narrative. In dialogue I can see it working. We say ""all of a sudden"" a lot  so keep that in mind too.   I also feel that there is too much about the main character and the shade. Like I feel that there's being too much thrown in a prologue. I really feel like if you want to worldbuild Endollon  you should focus on the Regnants in the following chapter and leave world building out of the prologue (if you decide to keep it as a prologue). Prologues should be teasers  and I feel that there is just too much info in this. I know I said that already  but it's something that I think could be worked on for this prologue.    Now what I liked a lot was the way you handled most of the descriptions. Nothing was lacking in meat  and the voice was pretty strong all the way through  so I compliment that and your ability to continue writing with precise lines. There was the line I loved the most and it was the dialogue with the shade. For some reason I felt the shade being raspy voiced  and when I read that it had a raspy voice  I wondered why I felt like that. I noticed that the shade needs more description of raspy stuff  but I feel like thatmight have been why since it's shadowy and almost ghost like.   Overall this is an enjoyable read  even if it was a little heavy on the detail for a prologue."

"Aw honey  I haven't read it yet  but I think your book seems awesome! It's great that you're trying to break cliches  and the ""keeping the readers afraid of the mc"" part is not only a good way to hook your readers  it's actually different from other books! Only a few books keep you genuinely worried about the characters (ASOIAF)  but in most of them  you're sure they're gonna come out victorious.  I totally get that thing about being down because of a review. I got one for my story Up  Up and Away once and even though most of it was still in a positive light  the negative parts hit me HARD. They were things I had never stopped to consider. Although I was (and still am) thankful to the reviewer  I began to question why on earth I was even bothering to write in the first place. I began to think that I was the worst writer on the face of the planet  and I was writing the most cringeworthy book of all time. What I decided from that was to not ask for my book to be properly reviewed until after I completed it. That way  I wouldn't break down half-way through and sit in mourning for the death of my confidence. But after a while  most (not all  I guess) of the insecurity wore off  and I felt more confident about writing. And the encouragement of my friends really helped too. If your readers think your work is good  if they like it  then that does half the trick!   Although it's important to actually like what you write  I think it's also natural for you to question parts of your book. Being blind to your own flaws can't possibly be of any help  so it's a good thing if you know where you're going wrong! That way  you can improve. (And not become full of yourself by thinking you've written the best book in the whole wide world.)   As your friend  all my support is with you. I hope you will be able to see your book in good light again soon.  red heart  red heart  red heart  red heart "

Hello there! Since you've expressed the desire of improving  so I've read this far and now I'm ready to give you a first opinion. You already know what I think of the introduction chapter  so I will focus more on the following two. The plot per se is very unique  so is the world you created and its system. I found the Monarch Trials interesting and the magic the gods wield certainly have potential. Having said that  I'm not sure I'm going to continue your story - here's why. The writing style had appropriate diction and proper grammar  however  I personally found it meagre  almost like a script  with plenty of well-constructed dialogue but no real narrative. Perhaps it was because of the need to explain a lot of stuff (I'lll come back to that)  but to me it felt fast and rushed. It caused  therefore  a lot of confusion in my head  specially with the character  which I wasn't able to identify. Expect for Edna  since it's her point of view  I have only blurry ideas of the other characters mentioned. They are reduced to their names  while I don't have an idea of how they look like  how they act  and what their personality is like. Your way of explaining background is clear and neat  however  I felt that it was definitely too much  to the point I personally don't have a real input to jump and read the next chapter. In many ways  it also felt obvious. I expected she was going to be a god  and that they'd put her on Earth for her protection. Again  the world you created and its players have tons of potential  which I envy  but they are not expressed to their fullest  thus  sounding to me both chaotic and simplistic. Last but not least  in terms of emotions  I personally didn't feel attached to Edna  in particular to her resistance to drink the medicine and come back to her real world. Mostly  it was because I didn't perceive the fifteen years she mentions  didn't feel the attachment she had to her life  despite the first chapter (which  if I may say  kind of (continues)

Try to use less adverbs during dialogue tags. Keep them simple (i.e. he said  she said) so that the action flows. Especially during an information bomb  it's best not to get too caught up on something as benign as a few little words. Otherwise it's great  thumbs up   smiling face with smiling eyes   The one part eating me alive was her heart condition. If it was as bad as the doctors said it was  she wouldn't be allowed to do any strenuous activity. So the prolonged scene in the second chapter where everyone is arguing and Edna has a gun is really stretching it. She would have had problems throughout the whole scene. When the first guy (blondie I believe  lol) appears out of nowhere  that would have given her an awful start.   Plus  holding a gun with the intent to shoot would skyrocket a heart rate. Not sure how much shooting experience you've had  but a gun is a very explosive weapon. A lot can go wrong  especially at such close range. Even if she's been trained to use it  that doesn't change the fight or flight response she would be having in the moment. The movies make it seem like nothing to fire away  but that's far from the reality.  ~ I really loved the opening line. I have waited a long  long time to write this comment.  From the very first sentence  your story enticed me. You claim that the villains are mere shadows of their potential  but I find them more solid than the phone in my hand. The motivations  the thoughts  the ideals that each character holds close to them make them so distinct  such an individual entity  that it shocked me. The pain that I felt when Tristan died was shocking. The silent sobbing was shocking. The sheer force of your words nearly bowled me over. Hours and hours  I have spent pouring over your work. You point out the flaws  but I want to bring to light the beautiful strengths that it has. The words themselves work alongside you. The imagery is stronger than a Robert Frost poem.  When you doubt yourself  just know that there are people like me. People who are devoted  who would bow down to the crown of words that you wear proudly.
The hardest task of all is to building something up  and know that you have to break it down and build it again.

Oh. My. Bleeding. Goodness. Where do I begin? I binge-read this whole book over the span of about 8 hours. And I legitimately feel like my life has changed. Ellis  you have left a lasting impact on every single one of your readers. I experience shock  I cried  I got horny (I need to go find some holy water)  I laughed. I laughed maniacally at 3 in the morning. I sobbed at 3 in the evening. You have given me so much life with this book. I admire every drop of sweat  blood and tears that you put into this book. All the details... they are glorious. Every inch of your pages are glorious. Every bit of your calloused fingers and minute if your screentime is glorious. It is wicked  it is wild  and most of all  you glorious goddess of a writer  it is wonderful. Thank you for giving us Crown and Glass. I pray that I shall be plucking this book off my shelf to read to my children  nestled between the works if Mary Shelley and Shakespeare. I pray that box office records are broken with movies inspired by this book. I pray that the actors that portray these characters break Oscar records. I pray that your name goes down in history  and is lauded in Harvard classrooms. Ellis  you have a God-given gift. Thank you for giving us a glimpse of it.

Despite those flaws  this book is still incredible. Its still a wonder of neatly tied up plot threads and terrifying villains who kill hundreds with a snap.
